# General Development Rules

## Mandatory

Before generating code:

- Read relevant architecture and product documentation.
- Follow the **current sprint scope**.
- Prefer simple, maintainable solutions.
- Reuse existing approved modules.
- Preserve backward compatibility where required.
- Use descriptive names; avoid unexplained magic values.
- Validate external input and handle expected failure states.
- Include tests for business logic.
- Update documentation when behaviour changes.
- State assumptions in comments or docs where necessary.
- Preserve existing formatting unless refactoring is requested.
- Avoid changing unrelated files.
- Avoid new dependencies unless necessary; explain and pin versions.
- Keep production code free from temporary debug code.

## Prohibited

- Rewriting a complete module when a focused change suffices.
- Removing security checks to make tests pass.
- Disabling null safety.
- Swallowing exceptions or using empty catch blocks.
- Using production credentials in examples.
- Storing tokens in source code.
- Creating duplicate models for the same contract without justification.
- Creating circular module dependencies.
- Adding global mutable state without architecture approval.
- Performing privileged writes from a client.
- Disabling tests or lint rules without explanation.
- Committing generated build output.
- Using placeholder implementations in production paths without marking them.
- Claiming work complete when tests fail.
- Introducing breaking protocol changes without versioning.

## Review checklist

- [ ] Matches sprint scope and allowed folders
- [ ] No unrelated file changes
- [ ] Tests added for behavioural changes
- [ ] Documentation updated where required
- [ ] No secrets or credentials introduced
